{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774407978,"nonce":"7H97DFEK9MMo6Z5OesFnNoOEPaw=","title":"Experimental plan: producing SISU-conditional robustness and velocity modulation","message":"## Goal\n\nProduce models where SISU demonstrably modulates both robustness (feedback gains) and peak velocity (trajectory planning). The velocity signature is the H-infinity prediction from Crevecoeur \u0026 Scott (2019).\n\n## Current status\n\nAll training methods tested (standard, CVaR, APT, with/without adaptive control cost) produce \u003c1% SISU→velocity effect. SISU DOES modulate accuracy (~11%), confirming it's used for feedback gains. See Bug: 3b70482 for detailed findings.\n\n## Ranked experimental suggestions\n\n### Tier 1: High information gain\n\n1. **Null-space analysis** (mechanistic, no new training): Project SISU-induced hidden state changes onto output-potent vs output-null subspaces using existing feedbax analysis tools (Jacobians, PCAResults, StatesPCA in part2.plant_perts). If SISU effects are mostly null-space, the network ignores SISU for motor output. This also includes SISU gradient map (d(output)/d(SISU) over time) and population-specific analysis (input/readout/recurrent).\n\n2. **Movement-time penalty** in loss: Explicit cost for time in transit. Under uncertainty, faster = less exposure = lower cost. This creates gradient pressure for SISU-conditional velocity that the current running_cost loss lacks.\n\n3. **True minimax training** with adversary network: Instead of fixed-adversary APT (Madry et al. 2018), use a learned adversary that adapts to the controller's strategy. This is the game-theoretic structure that H-infinity theory requires for trajectory-level modulation. See Bug: 84ee4ff. Analysis of stability/implementation in progress.\n\n4. **SISU mismatch eval**: Evaluate with real perturbations but clamped SISU (SISU=0 when pert is present, SISU=1 when no pert). If performance is identical regardless of SISU, SISU is unused for robustness.\n\n5. **SISU lesioning**: Zero SISU input weights, re-evaluate. If no performance drop, SISU was never load-bearing.\n\n### Tier 2: Architectural modifications\n\n6. **Strategy embedding network**: Secondary network (SISU + state → 16-dim embedding) modulates main GRU via initial hidden state h0. Creates richer strategy representation than scalar.\n\n7. **Multiplicative SISU gating**: h * (1 + α*SISU) instead of additive input. Mimics neuromodulatory gain control.\n\n8. **Separate estimator-controller**: Two GRUs — estimator (feedback + SISU → state estimate) → controller (estimate + SISU + target → motor). H-infinity separation principle breaks down precisely because estimation and control are coupled.\n\n9. **Larger networks**: 360-720 units. Rules out capacity bottleneck.\n\n### Tier 3: Training modifications\n\n10. **Curriculum**: Separate β=0 and β=1 training epochs, then fine-tune on U[0,1].\n\n11. **Control cost ratio sweep**: Wider range of target_ratio values. Current 0.3-0.5 may be too narrow. The \"right\" ratio might exist where being too robust at SISU=0 is costly enough to force switching.\n\n12. **SISU-conditional loss shaping**: L = (1-β)*L_efficient + β*L_robust with different penalty structures.\n\n## Mechanistic analysis plan\n\nUsing existing feedbax infrastructure (Jacobians, Hessians, PCA, Profiles):\n1. SISU gradient map: |d(output_t)/d(SISU)| over time\n2. Output-potent vs null decomposition\n3. Population-specific SISU effects (input/readout/recurrent)\n4. PCA of SISU-conditional trajectory differences\n5. Fixed-point analysis at SISU=0 vs SISU=1 (Sussillo \u0026 Barak 2013)\n6. Linearized dynamics: Jacobian eigenvalue spectrum comparison\n7. Feedback gain estimation via probe perturbations (part2.plant_perts)\n\n## Cross-references\n- Bug: 3b70482 — SISU-conditional velocity absent despite prerequisites\n- Bug: 84ee4ff — Worst-case training methods\n- Bug: ce34c2c — GRU laziness and architecture choice\n- Bug: 31043a5 — Adaptation vs robustness distinguishability","files":null}]}